roblem is presented in a systematic-theoretical rather than historical manner. The main aim of this book is a retrospective film theoretical rehabilitation of the psychoanalytical concept of "suture," whose political core is progressively revealed. In a second step, this rereading of ''suture''-theory is mediated with the Marxist aesthetics of Fredric Jameson. From the perspective of this reconfigured aesthetics of negativity, films by Hitchcock, Antonioni, Haneke and Kubrick are analyzed as articulations of a political unconscious.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCommunist aesthetics. 0aCommunists in motion pictures. 0aMotion picturesxAesthetics. 0aMotion picturesxPolitical aspects. 0aPolitics in motion pictures. 4aFilm Theory. 4aFilm, Media and Communication. 4aMedia Studies. 4aModern Period. 4aPolitical Science. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh  aFilm Theory, Aesthetics, Politics, Psychoanalysis, Marxism,.1 aFairfax, Daniel.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package 2020z978311068955608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertArt and Architecture eBook-Package 2020z978311073823008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2020z9783110704655oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2020 Englishz978311070478508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048533985zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048533985423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789048533985.jpg  a978-3-11-068955-6  AUP eBook Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070